So grateful for my family, who fully support (/enable) all my ridiculousness. 🥰 Happy holidays!

Wrapping up 2022: More than anything, I’m proud of myself for GOING FOR IT full-tilt this year. I dubbed this my “year of actually trying,” because I usually shy away from things I don’t think I’d be good at and make a joke of them instead of actually giving my best effort. While it can be fun to make a mockery of things, there’s so much value in actually putting yourself out there and trying new things that scare you. I’m hopeful that 2023 will bring great things for me as a result of my efforts, but either way, it’s all about the journey — and I’m feeling great about mine. Cheers to a new year of happiness and prosperity! 🥂
.
.

An underreported fact about my cat George is that he’s an absolute computer whiz. For example, I can step away for only a minute and come back to George sitting on the keyboard of my work laptop, somehow having emailed my boss 674 lines of utter nonsense, made a purchase for an infinite supply of Chia pets, deleted every important file, and then shut my computer down completely — all within the span of a minute, mind you. I can’t even turn my computer off that quickly when the clock strikes 5 and I’m ready to be done for the day, so that takes skill. Bravo, George.

One thing I admire about George is how responsive and perceptive he is. When I can’t find him, I don’t have to search for long, because if I call out for him, he will appear out of thin air… often yawning because I’ve woken him up from a well-deserved catnap. But the truly scary part is that I can just be talking ABOUT George instead of TO him and he will still come around. You better believe that I’ve long learned my lesson when it comes to talking about George behind his back! 😸😅

When the reality TV version of Squid Game: The Challenge was first announced, people asked, “Who’s crazy enough to willingly sign up for that game?” Well, you’re looking at Player 436. 🙃 #SquidGameTheChallenge is now streaming on @netflix! #SquidGame #SquidGameNetflix

Wrapping up my #SquidGameTheChallenge experience as Player 436…

Anyone who knows me knows that it’s been one of my biggest life dreams to be on a reality competition show ever since I watched the first season of Survivor at 10 years old. So, when I got eliminated AFTER crossing the finish line of Red Light, Green Light, it felt like my dream went as horribly wrong as it possibly could. At the same time, I gave it my all, playing for 7.5+ hours in a freezing-cold room and never breaking despite having to hold each of my positions for 15+ minutes at a time (and sometimes much longer). I did cross the finish line with time left on the clock, but I was still eliminated, which crushed me.

However, I’ve learned a lot by dealing with this loss over the past year. No, I did not accomplish my goal – not by a longshot – but I’m proud of myself for taking a risk and giving it my all. I’ve realized that I can maintain a positive mindset and continue believing in myself even when things don’t go my way. I will keep going at it in hopes that I’m able to fully and truly live out my dream someday. And if it doesn’t happen? That’s okay, too! It won’t break me, and I can now say that with certainty. I’m still grateful to have had the opportunity to live out my childhood dream, if only for a brief moment, and I met some incredible people while doing it.

To the next big opportunity – I’m ready for it!
